Prelude
"Please, don't send her away!" Queen Alvin pleaded, "She's just a child!" The Ice King sat on his throne, looking down at his wife, with royal advisors standing by. The queen had given birth to a girl. At the thought of this, the Ice King couldn't help but furrow his brow.
The infant girl looked just like her mother: pale blue eyes, snow-white hair, with a few strands of blue hair. The Ice King thought having a daughter would make him look weak. After all, before this, he had only sons.
"You have only two choices, either kill the child or leave her out in the wilderness. Alvin, this is your punishment." He spat out her name as if it were poison. He always did.
The Kingdom of Frost wasn't always a single kingdom. It was once divided into two parts, north and south. The north established a non-magical kingdom, while the south became a kingdom filled with magical power. Due to the north's greed, the two kingdoms engaged in endless wars until the south proposed a truce.
At that time, the south had already fallen into despair, and the royal family was willing to do anything to stop this bloody conflict. They proposed marrying their only princess to the north, making her the queen of the north and having a son who would become the future king. Afterward, the south would merge with the north to establish a unified kingdom. The north accepted this proposal, and Princess Alvin thus married Prince Acur.
"Please, my king, for the safety of my child, you can do anything to me—imprison me, exile me, even kill me." Queen Alvin pleaded, holding the child tightly in her arms.
The Ice King looked down at the queen, his eyes filled with disdain. Perhaps, just perhaps, he would feel a sliver of pity for her. After all, this woman had been by his side for 22 years, cared for him during his lowest moments, and had given him children.
"Alright. The child can live in the palace." The queen sighed in relief at the Ice King's words. "But," he added, "you will be executed."
The royal advisors and Queen Alvin both showed expressions of terror. She slowly lowered her head and looked at the floor. "As you command, my king." She bowed.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisors to take the queen's daughter to an unused room in Alvin's palace. After that, he commanded the guards to take Alvin to the public execution ground where all the citizens could see.
As the guards escorted her to the execution ground, the citizens saw their only queen—and the kindest queen—about to be executed, and they became very angry. Some cried, some shouted and tried to attack the guards, and others wanted to know why such a thing had happened; but they all had the same question.
"Let her go!"
"Why are they treating her this way?"
As Alvin approached the wooden post, the most feared person in the kingdom appeared. He was the executioner for the burning. The former queen Alvin was to be burned alive. No one should be subjected to burning, not even criminals. In the Kingdom of Frost, burning was the cruelest punishment.
Alvin was bound to the wooden post as the king began to speak of how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of the Kingdom of Frost refused to believe and would never accept the king's words. Then, the executioner lit the wooden post, and a single tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
"Carly, live on!" Queen Alvin's life came to an end.
The hall was silent.
In the southern wing of this icy palace, an endless "tapping" sound came from the room on the far left. Past servants were always curious about what was inside the room but were too frightened to approach. The maids moved about the hall, whispering and spreading various rumors. Some believed that the Ice King's late wife, Alvin, was living in this room, waiting to be released.
They are very mistaken. As Avery thought, he walked toward the southern wing, where the servants moved along the walls, whispering to one another. They had no idea what was inside.
Of course, there were also many rumors about TA, as TA was the only one allowed to enter the room.
Knocked on the door. "Miss Carly, are you inside?" Avery whispered to this complicated door, adorned with snowflakes and a crown, symbols of the royal family.
TA didn't know if he would actually be allowed in this time, unlike before. I still had the bruises from last time, Avery recalled, and couldn't help but laugh. At that time, Carly had thrown a book at him, but when she realized who it was, she immediately apologized.
A soft sound came from the room, as if saying she couldn't go anywhere, but had to stay right there.
"May I come in?" Avery asked, not forgetting the consequences of last time when he had entered without being invited.
A soft sound came again from the room, as if saying, "Come in." Avery felt a chill, unsure whether it was from the cold or the voice. Although TA had been there for many years, Avery still found it a bit strange to hear the sound coming from the room.
"I'm coming in," Avery said, slowly opening the door. By normal standards, the scene inside the room was quite unusual, but this was expected. Papers were everywhere. Books were scattered on the floor, the table was broken, and there were many ice sculptures in the room. There were no windows, and there was almost no light. It was also colder here than anywhere else in the palace (which indicated many problems). The room looked as if it had been hit by a blizzard, everything was in a mess.
The girl in the room was curled up in bed, wrapped in blankets, reading a notebook. A small lantern lit up the room.
"What notebook are you reading?" Avery asked, sitting beside Carly's bed.
